               <p>WILLIAM BONSFIELD. I am a <rs id="t18130407-160-viclabel866" type="occupation">publican</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18130407-160-victim1357 t18130407-160-viclabel866"></join>; I keep <placeName id="t18130407-160-crimeloc867">the Cherry Tree, Whitecross-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18130407-160-crimeloc867" type="placeName" value="the Cherry Tree, Whitecross-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18130407-160-crimeloc867" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18130407-160-off864 t18130407-160-crimeloc867"></join>. I lost my shoes on the 22nd of March. The prisoner came in and had a pint of beer, and a pipe of tobacco, he paid for it, and as he went out I thought he had something sticking out, more than what he ought to have. A short time after that, I missed my shoes. On the 7th of April, I met him, and took him into my house. I sent for an officer; he denied taking them; he afterwards conffessed to the officer and me, that he took them, and sold them in Field-lane. I have never seen my shoes since.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18130407-160-person1358">
                  ROBERT 
                  LOCK
               <interp inst="t18130407-160-person1358" type="surname" value="LOCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130407-160-person1358" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18130407-160-person1358" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner confessed before the magistrate that he took the shoes, and sold them in Field-lane, for four shillings.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I am as innocent as a child unborn. I was frightened to confess it.</p>
               <p>
                  <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181304070088"></xptr>GUILTY, aged 20.</p>
